### Remote Attestation over EDHOC
**Presenter:** Yuxuan
* **Slides:** [05-Remote Attestation over EDHOC](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-lake-remote-attestation-over-edhoc-00)
* **Draft:** `draft-ietf-lake-ra`
* **Updates (v05 & v06):**
  * Section 6 was reorganized to cover all permutations of remote attestation across two dimensions: Target (Initiator or Responder) and Model (Background Check or Passport). The third dimension was removed.
  * The draft now explicitly defines both intra-handshake attestation (evidence in message 3) and post-handshake attestation (evidence in message 4).
  * Added an authorization binder to cryptographically link the attestation evidence to the authentication session. 
* **Discussion:**
  * Usama questioned the utility of intra-handshake attestation, claiming that because attestation is a point-in-time check, one-time attestation is insufficient and must be performed repeatedly post-handshake. He also stated that vulnerabilities in attested TLS apply equally to attested EDHOC and requested an implementation link to demonstrate a concrete attack.
  * Göran Selander responded that in certain applications (such as smart locks), a handshake is run dynamically on every physical interaction, making simultaneous authentication and attestation highly valuable.
  * The chairs directed the implementation sharing and attack demonstration to be handled offline.

