### Post-Quantum EDHOC Design Team Summary
**Presenter:** Renzo Navas
* **Slides:** [08-PQ-EDHOC-DT-Summary-IETF126Presentation](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-lake-08-pq-edhoc-dt-summary-ietf126presentation-00)
* **Summary:** The design team completed its work with four main objectives:
  * **Objective 1 (Deployment Scenarios):** Evaluated memory footprint (RAM/flash), link-layer MTU, and transmission times over Cortex-M4. Results indicated that PSK and KEM-based authentication methods have the lowest memory overhead and can fit Class 1 devices. Signature-based options require more memory (Class 2), but they reduce network overhead (fragmentation) over low-bandwidth links at the cost of CPU cycles.
  * **Objective 2 (PQ Cipher Suites):** Recommended adoption of post-quantum cipher suites. This resulted in the adoption of `draft-ietf-lake-pqsuites`.
  * **Objective 3 (KEM Authentication):** Recommended KEM-based mutual authentication, leading to the adoption of `draft-ietf-lake-authkem-edhoc`. Mixed authentication methods are currently out of scope.
  * **Objective 4 (CFRG Input):** Open. Highlighted the need for compact PQC schemes on highly constrained networks.

